# Translation handling

When adding or changing user-facing text:

1. **Use translation keys in code**  
   Use `useTranslations()` (or `getTranslations()` on the server) and call `t("key.path")`. Never hardcode user-facing strings in components.

2. **Add entries in all locale files**  
   Add or update the same key in every file under `messages/` (e.g. `messages/en.json`, `messages/ar.json`). Keep keys and structure identical across locales.

3. **Key structure**  
   Use nested keys by feature: `auth.signIn.title`, `auth.signIn.email.placeholder`, `page.error.default`. Match the structure used in existing messages.

4. **Validation and API errors**  
   Zod schemas and API error handling should use translation keys (e.g. `auth.validation.email.invalid`). In the UI, pass those keys through `t()` so the message is shown in the current locale.

5. **Types**  
   Message keys are typed via `i18n/types.d.ts` (from `messages/en.json`). After changing JSON, TypeScript will enforce that only existing keys are used.

Example:

```tsx
const t = useTranslations()
// ✅ Use keys
<Title>{t("auth.signIn.title")}</Title>
<TextInput placeholder={t("auth.signIn.email.placeholder")} />
// ❌ Don't hardcode
<Title>Sign in</Title>
```

In `messages/en.json` and `messages/ar.json`:

```json
"auth": {
  "signIn": {
    "title": "Sign in to your account",
    "email": { "placeholder": "Enter your email" }
  }
}
```
